thread.title: Nutley wrestling shows 2nd life, advances in North 2, Group 3 Tournament
thread.title_full: Nutley wrestling shows 2nd life, advances in North 2, Group 3 Tournament

author: Patrick Lanni | NJ Advance Media for NJ.com
title: Nutley wrestling shows 2nd life, advances in North 2, Group 3 Tournament
text:
Daily schedule 
After starting 1-7, Nutley is through to the state semifinals. 
It's a noteworthy turn-around for a team that three weeks ago was on the verge of a opting out of the postseason. 
"We talked about not entering, but we got through it," said Nutley coach Mike DiPiano following his team's 31-30 win over Rahway in the first round of the North Jersey, Section 2, Group 3 Tournament on Monday night. 
Low numbers and several season-ending injuries started to wear on a team that was a No. 1 seed last year and a sectional finalist two years ago. 
"This team could have made the decision to bag it, and they chose not to," said DiPiano, whose team is now 14-9. "They come to work every day, and they’re starting to believe in the concept.” 
Nutley overcame three Rahway pins to start the match by winning seven straight bouts from 138-195. Freshman Daniel Jennings picked up a key 6-5 decision at 182 against Rahway's Sam Dorielan while Frank DeMaio and Aaron Dunn won by fall at 138 and 145, respectively. 
Despite losing at 220 and heavyweight, David Sanchez and Luis Abreu avoided giving up bonus points. DiPiano those two losses "won him the match by saving six points." 
From there Dominic Cofone sealed the match with a 6-2 decision at 106 before Nutley forfeited the final weight to preserve its one-point victory on the road. 
With the win, Nutley, the No. 5 seed, heads to Cranford to take on the top-seeded and state-ranked No. 4 Cougars in the semifinals on Wednesday. 
"We know that we're out-matched, but we're going to go there, punch them in the mouth and see what happens," DiPiano said. "It gives us the opportunity to win several bouts and put on a good showing to get us ready for Districts."
